  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as funds from criminal activities) appear legal by disguising their true origin. This is typically done by passing the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the United States, for example, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** are key pieces of legislation that criminalize money laundering and require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions. Additionally, the **Patriot Act** strengthened anti-money laundering (AML) measures after the 9/11 terrorist attacks.\n\nInternationally, money laundering is also prohibited through agreements like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** recommendations, which provide a global standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Countries that are part of the FATF or other international organizations are expected to implement laws and regulations to prevent and penalize money laundering.\n\nConsequences for money laundering can include severe penalties, such as imprisonment, hefty fines, and asset forfeiture, depending on the jurisdiction and the severity of the offense.",
